          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A pathologist examines a biopsy and sees striated fibres with centrally placed nuclei connected by specialised junctions. Which muscle tissue is this?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Skeletal muscle</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Skeletal muscle is striated but its nuclei are peripheral, not central. The peripheral position of nuclei is the key histological marker for skeletal muscle.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Cardiac muscle</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Cardiac muscle is striated with centrally placed nuclei and intercalated discs — specialised junctions that coordinate rhythmic contraction of the myocardium.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Smooth muscle</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Smooth muscle has central nuclei but it is non-striated. The presence of striations in the biopsy rules out smooth muscle.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Visceral striated muscle</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Visceral striated muscle (e.g., oesophageal) is histologically identical to skeletal muscle with peripheral nuclei. Central nuclei with striations point to cardiac tissue.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The combination of striations + central nuclei + specialised junctions identifies cardiac muscle. Skeletal muscle has peripheral nuclei; smooth muscle lacks striations."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Cardiac muscle uniquely combines three features: striations, central nuclei, and intercalated discs. Remember the S-V-P rule — Skeletal = Striated + Voluntary + Peripheral nuclei."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
