          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Which connective tissue layer directly wraps individual muscle fibres and is the</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which connective tissue layer directly wraps individual muscle fibres and is the site where capillaries make contact?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Epimysium</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The epimysium is the outermost layer — it wraps the entire muscle as a dense connective tissue coat, not individual fibres.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Perimysium</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The perimysium wraps fascicles (bundles of fibres) and carries blood vessels and nerves toward the fibres, but does not directly envelop each fibre.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Endomysium</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The endomysium is the innermost connective tissue layer, wrapping each individual muscle fibre. Capillaries and nerve terminals make direct contact here.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Sarcolemma</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The sarcolemma is the plasma membrane of the muscle fibre itself — not a connective tissue layer. Connective tissue layers are extracellular wrappings derived from the extracellular matrix.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Remember the hierarchy: epimysium wraps the whole muscle, perimysium wraps fascicles, and endomysium wraps each individual fibre. Capillaries reach fibres at the endomysium level."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "The hierarchy runs outside-in: epimysium (whole muscle) → perimysium (fascicle) → endomysium (individual fibre). Nutrient and nerve exchange occurs at the endomysium."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
