          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>When catching a fast-moving ball, which muscle becomes proportionally more activ</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>When catching a fast-moving ball, which muscle becomes proportionally more active to prevent the elbow joint surfaces from separating?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Brachialis</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The brachialis is a spurt muscle — its line of pull passes mostly across the bone, producing angular movement at the elbow, not joint stabilisation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Biceps brachii</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The biceps brachii is also a spurt muscle at the elbow. It creates angular movement but is not primarily responsible for compressing the joint surfaces together.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Brachioradialis</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The brachioradialis is the key shunt muscle at the elbow. Its pull runs along the bone, compressing joint surfaces and preventing separation during rapid movements.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Triceps brachii</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The triceps is the extensor of the elbow and opposes flexion. It is not classified as the shunt muscle that stabilises the joint during rapid flexion.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "In MacConaill's classification, spurt muscles (brachialis, biceps) create movement while shunt muscles (brachioradialis) stabilise the joint by compressing its surfaces — especially critical during rapid actions like catching."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Shunt muscles like the brachioradialis act along the bone to compress and stabilise the joint. They work alongside spurt muscles (brachialis, biceps) which create the angular movement."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
